Here's the consolidated list of different types of JavaScript function calls that can be used in HTML, categorized with examples:

Basic 


id="123" class="main"

1. Event Handlers:
   - `<button @click={clickHandler}>Click Me</button>`
   - `<button onclick="clickHandler()">Click Me</button>`
   - `<button onclick={clickHandler}>Click Me</button>`

2. Attribute-style:
   - `<button click={clickHandler}>Click Me</button>`
   - `<button onClick={clickHandler}>Click Me</button>`


3. JS-only:
   - `<button onclick="javascript:clickHandler()">Click Me</button>`

4. Function Call:
   - `<button onclick="clickHandler(param1, param2)">Click Me</button>`



5. Arrow Function:
   - `<button onclick={() => clickHandler()}>Click Me</button>`

6. Immediately Invoked Function Expression (IIFE):
   - `<button onclick={(function(){ clickHandler() })()}>Click Me</button>`



7. JS Eval:
   - `<button onclick="eval('clickHandler()')">Click Me</button>`

8. String-based:
   - `<button onclick="clickHandler.toString()">Click Me</button>`

9. Object Method Call:
   - `<button onclick="obj.method()">Click Me</button>`
   - `<button onclick="obj['method']()">Click Me</button>`
   - `<button onclick={() => obj.method()}>Click Me</button>`
   - `<button onclick={() => obj['method']()}>Click Me</button>`

These examples cover various ways JavaScript functions can be called and executed within HTML elements.

